---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const baseUrl = 'https://icontree.cosmoscope.workers.dev';

const promptText = `# Task: Integrate IconTree Icons Into Existing App

## Objective
Add IconTree-powered Lottie icons to an existing app screen/feature.
This is an INTEGRATION task, not a new-product task.

## Target
- App/Framework: [FILL IN — e.g. React + Vite, Flutter, React Native, plain HTML/JS]
- Screen or component being modified: [FILL IN — e.g. "Sidebar nav", "Settings screen"]
- Existing Lottie library already in use (if any): [FILL IN, e.g. lottie-react, lottie-web, lottie_flutter, lottie-react-native]

## Hard Constraints — Do NOT
- Do NOT build a new icon library, browser, or gallery UI.
- Do NOT build an icon marketplace or catalog page.
- Do NOT recreate or clone IconTree's own search UI/backend.
- Do NOT invent API fields, endpoints, or response properties beyond what's specified below.
- Do NOT introduce a new design system, new color tokens, or new layout patterns — reuse what the app already has (spacing, sizing, theme colors, component conventions).
- Do NOT add a search UI if the request is manual/local mode.
- Do NOT make network calls if the request is manual/local mode.
- Do NOT output unrelated boilerplate (no new app scaffold, no README, no unrelated files) — only the code needed for this specific feature.

## IconTree Reference

Base URL: \`${baseUrl}\`

### Mode 1 — API mode (search + fetch remote icon JSON)
Use when icons should be searched/selected dynamically at runtime.

- Endpoint: \`GET /icon/search\`
- Query params (only these — no others):
  - \`q\` — search term (string)
  - \`category\` — category filter (string, optional)
  - \`page\` — page number (integer, optional)
  - \`pageSize\` — results per page (integer, optional)
- Response shape (assume only these fields exist):
\`\`\`json
  {
    "results": [
      { "url": "/relative/path/to/icon.json", ...other fields may exist but are NOT to be relied on unless explicitly requested }
    ]
  }
\`\`\`
- To get a usable icon JSON:
  1. Call \`GET ${baseUrl}/icon/search?q=...&category=...&page=...&pageSize=...\`
  2. Read \`response.results[]\`
  3. For each result, build full URL: \`${baseUrl}{result.url}\`
  4. Fetch that URL to get the Lottie JSON animation data
  5. Pass that JSON into the platform's Lottie player component

### Mode 2 — Manual mode (pre-downloaded local JSON)
Use when the specific icon \`.json\` files have already been chosen/downloaded and bundled into the app.

- Assume files already exist locally at: [FILL IN — e.g. \`src/assets/icons/\`, \`assets/lottie/\`, \`public/icons/\`]
- Load them the standard way for the platform (import, require, asset bundle reference, etc. — whichever is idiomatic for the stack above)
- Pass the loaded JSON into the platform's Lottie player component
- No network requests, no search params, no dynamic fetching

## Implementation Requirements
1. Match the existing component structure and naming conventions already used in the app.
2. Reuse existing styling (className/theme/tokens) — do not hardcode new colors, spacing, or sizes unless the current design system requires a new token for this feature.
3. Icon size, loop, autoplay, and other Lottie player props should be configurable via props/parameters, not hardcoded, unless the app's convention is to hardcode such values elsewhere.
4. Handle loading and error states appropriately for API mode (e.g. fetch failure, empty results) using the app's existing patterns for async state (loading spinners, error boundaries, etc.) — don't invent a new pattern if one already exists.
5. Manual mode requires no loading/error state beyond standard asset-not-found handling, since data is local.
6. Code must be directly droppable into the existing codebase — assume it will be pasted into the file(s) indicated in "Target" above.

## Output Format
- Return only the code required for this feature (component(s)/function(s) needed).
- No extra scaffolding, no unrelated files, no explanatory essay — a short comment above non-obvious logic is fine.
- If both modes are relevant, clearly separate them into two distinct, clearly labeled code blocks (do not mix search logic into manual mode or vice versa).
- Production-ready: proper typing (if the stack uses TypeScript/Dart typing), no placeholder TODOs left unresolved, no console.log debugging left in.`;
---

<Layout title="IconTree - AI Prompt">
  <div class="doc-content doc-content-wide prompt-shell">
    <div class="doc-nav">
      <a href="/" class="back-link">&lt; Back</a>
    </div>

    <section class="doc-hero">
      <span class="doc-kicker">AI Prompt</span>
      <h1>One Prompt to Use IconTree</h1>
      <p class="doc-lead">
        This prompt is for adding IconTree icons into an existing app, not for building a new icon library.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="prompt-card">
      <h3>Prompt</h3>
      <p>Copy this prompt into your AI tool when you want it to build or integrate IconTree correctly.</p>
      <pre><code>{promptText}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="lang-grid" aria-label="Prompt guidance">
      <article class="lang-card">
        <h3>Structure</h3>
        <p>
          The prompt tells the AI three things clearly: use the existing app, choose API or manual mode, and only
          write integration code for that app feature.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="lang-card">
        <h3>How to Add It</h3>
        <p>
          Paste the prompt first, then add one short line about your stack and target screen, like “Use React on the
          settings page” or “Use Android Kotlin in the onboarding screen”.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-callout">
      <p><strong>Example add-on lines</strong></p>
      <ul class="prompt-list">
        <li><code>Use React and Tailwind.</code></li>
        <li><code>Use Android Kotlin with a LottieAnimationView.</code></li>
        <li><code>Use manual local JSON files, not remote API calls.</code></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script>
    (function() {
      const preBlocks = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('.doc-content pre')) as HTMLElement[];

      preBlocks.forEach((pre: HTMLElement) => {
        const btn = document.createElement('button');
        btn.className = 'copy-snippet-btn';
        btn.textContent = 'Copy';
        btn.type = 'button';
        pre.style.position = 'relative';
        pre.appendChild(btn);

        btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
          const code = pre.querySelector('code');
          const text = code?.textContent || '';

          navigator.clipboard.writeText(text).then(() => {
            btn.textContent = 'Copied!';
            btn.classList.add('copied');

            setTimeout(() => {
              btn.textContent = 'Copy';
              btn.classList.remove('copied');
            }, 2000);
          });
        });
      });
    })();
  </script>
</Layout>
